Come to the pink side, we have robots.

If promoting STEM among minorities makes me a bad influence, then I WANT TO BE A BAD INFLUENCE!

This is something I am super passionate about and definitely enjoy, at the same time that I encourage them to be themselves.

We can be engineers, scientists, programmers, researchers, and we can also do it in heels, glitter, pink, or anything that fully makes us feel like ourselves.

Not because I love pink, everyone must like it as well. However, it opens the door for everyone to feel welcomed expressing themselves as they truly are without having to feel uncomfortable or that they don’t belong in these fields.

Some have told me that I have encouraged them to be more feminine, something they felt they had to stop because they were in engineering. I did the same thing and wore mostly men shirts my last 2 years of college. Not anymore!

So, keep rocking those shoes, colors, or accessories and keep rocking it in STEM.

I will be here cheering for you.

This is how I was able to buy the house of my dreams before I was 25!

📌 I chose an affordable college. (community college then a school that was not “prestige” but got me the degree). This meant I had no big loans or that all my money had to go to pay for school.

📌 I picked an emphasis for my career of something that is in high demand and would lower the risk of losing my job or not finding one: Engineering & later automation.

📌I lived with my parents. I never moved out for college and when I graduated, I also stayed for the first 8 months which meant I could save a ton during that time with my new engineering salary.

📌 I kept a tight budget. I always knew where my money was going. I did include a budget to eat out and buy things here and there but held off on bigger purchases like having the latest tech.

📌 I always negotiated my pay to make sure it was fair, aligned with the market and met needs. I also always went above and beyond to show my dedication and qualifications when it was time to negotiate.

📌 I teamed up. I went straight from my parents to living with my partner, so I never had to pay full rent/mortgage. This is also how we doubled our income because it was 2 of us after 1 goal. We also rented one of our extra bed rooms for the first 6 months.

📌 I planned, and planned, and planned. Or at least my partner did, and I made sure we sticked to it.
We waited and acted fast once an opportunity was available.

We both came from families with different situations and challenges. We are also both from immigrant families. So, it was important for us to achieve big plans to help us be financially stable and able to prepare for the future needs or situations.

We have been able to get far by always planning ahead rather than solemnly focus on the moment and doing good things for ourselves and others. And we are finally getting to a point where we can start to plan for extra things such as trips and gifts. Of course always with a budget.

I hope our story inspires you.

Let’s get our money!

The average Latina only makes 54 cents per every dollar that a white man makes.

Now, there is a lot that goes into this such as the types of jobs that we are taking! As an engineer, I feel that I am not at such a drastic difference as what the average represents. This has all been thanks to the type of career I chose, how I negotiate, my work ethic, and the companies I choose to work.

I did not go to the best schools, I do not work in a big city (I’m in the farthest suburbs that you can be from Chicago), and I am not in a prestige field such as aerospace. Yet there are still good opportunities! This is why I promote STEM so much!

So, let’s diversify STEM and get the money we deserve while we are at it.

Note: It is not only up to us. Like I said part of it has to do with what companies I choose that promote my growth. So, if you are a manager, talent acquisition, own a company or can influence in any way, there is also a lot of work to do from your end as well!

You all really don’t want me to bring up the time I was a more experienced intern getting paid less than my less experienced white coworker. (And yes I did bring it up that time and yes I was able to get what I was missing out on)

#latinaequalpayday #equalpayday #paygap #latinapower #latinasintech #salarynegotiation #careermotivation

I’ve been navigating the fact of using it to our advantage. While some might say that we “only got it” referring to our jobs, scholarships, acceptance, etc. because they needed diversity numbers, I like to see it as an advantage that we can use.

Trust me, no one is going to hire you or give you a scholarship just because you have minority in you. We still got to meet all the other requirements. We must also have the skills! Then being a minority can help us stand out.

Reality is, those schools, programs and companies do need the diversity numbers. Let’s bee happy they are trying to expand their horizons. But also know that they aren’t just going to hire anyone. However, if you meet the requirements and support their diversity increase efforts, boom! Shoot two birds with one stone.

So yes, I use being a Latina to my advantage when necessary. We already lack of too much privilege that non-minorities have, so let’s stop putting ourselves down for standing out as a desirable candidate.

Apply to those scholarships where being a minority woman will give you higher chances. Show up to those interviews and show them that your bilingual skills make you twice as valuable. We deserve this.

There are a couple of things that were big red flags during my past job as well as during interviews when looking for a new job!

We spend so much time at work that we NEED to be picky about how it fits with our plans and goals.

These were my top 5:

1️⃣They expect you to be always available. This one really is tricky. My employees work across all 3 shifts which means there is almost always working. So while I cannot just turn off my cellphone completely, I do prioritize what really is an urgency and what is not. I even have my email notifications off so I can only check it when I decide to. But I have had interviews where they would state that I would have to put in unpaid overtime from the get-go. It was a hard no for me.

2️⃣Seeing your unrelated job activities as a threat. Whether it is a hobby, volunteering, etc. and having that idea that it is distracting you from work. I went from a place that did not support my non-profit or one that donated to my foundation!

3️⃣If your manager does not do regular check ins to truly learn how you are doing and what you need to be successful. This is why I like working in a smaller team.

4️⃣If you are afraid of asking for simple things that will help you do your job or they are counting cents, how are you ever going to be successful. I even ordered a new desk chair because my old was affecting my ability to work comfortably.

4️⃣If you cannot be yourself and have to hide your Latinindad in order to fit in. Or if you are surrounded by others who think anything than white traditions is weird. Get out of there!

There will be things that will definitely give you an advantage when it comes to engineering but by no means does that mean that you will not be successful without them. 

Engineering is always seemed as a hard degree, which it is. however, whether you graduated with an A or a C doesn’t really matter. Rarely do companies ask for transcripts and the goal is that you can actually apply what you learn not how well you test. A lot of us as minorities tend to have disadvantages at school such as having to work full time during the semester or learning a language. Don’t worry so much about having the perfect scores as long as you are still on track.

I also wanted to emphasize on the fact that we do not need to fit in in order to succeed. I was guilty of trying to blend in, and even wear guys clothes in order to look like I belonged. At work everyone wore polos in the summer, so I naturally started gravitating towards those as well. But then I realized that I would not feel confident in how I looked. Dressing more girly and professional made me feel better, so I ditched the jeans and expressed myself and it honestly reflects in my work. 

Lastly, you didn’t have to know what you wanted to do when you were 5. Some of us, it took us until college to figure it out.  Many weren’t interested in Legos, or cars, or tools before engineering and they are still doing an excellent job at work.

So, keep being you and keep pushing forward. If you are passionate about your career and you keep working hard you will be successful.

This happens to many women when they decide to study engineering especially when they are first generation students.

 

That was not actually the case from me, because my dad studied engineering and my mom industrial design. However, once my mom started hearing some of my talks and seeing how other girls identified with my story and found inspiration on what I do, she realized how hard and lonely it can get. I have also seen some of her friends’ reactions of horror when any of their daughters pick a STEM career.

 

Some of these reactions come from a mixture of reasons:

 

1. Not knowing of the opportunities that STEM careers bring to women, especially when it comes to salary, independence and fulfillment.

2.  Fear of facing a harsh environment when going into a male dominated field. And worrying that would cause us to give up on our career.

3.  Language barriers, or not being familiar with the field where they could give us advice when we face obstacles.

 

Whatever the reason it is, it is important that we express our interest and continue pursuing our passions. We might not always be able to convince everyone, but that does not mean we must give up on our goals.

 

If you want to meet more Ingenieras to empower you in your journey through engineering, make sure to be following us and subscribe to our newsletter. We do Ingeniera shout outs, host brunches, and an annual conference in the fall that every year is bigger and better!

Becoming a leader at a young age can be an overwhelming task, but it is not impossible. Here are some tips to help you achieve this goal:

1. Set clear goals: Having a clear vision of what you want to achieve is crucial. Set specific and measurable goals that will help you work towards becoming a manager. 

2. Build a strong network: Networking is essential in any career. Spend time learning form other leaders in the company. Attend events, conferences, and connect with people in your industry. Building a strong network will help you learn from others and gain new opportunities.

3. Gain relevant experience: Experience is key to becoming a successful manager. Look for internships, part-time jobs, or volunteer opportunities that will give you the skills and knowledge needed to excel in your field.

4. Learn continuously: Keep yourself updated with the latest trends and developments in your industry. Read books, attend courses, and learn from experts. Continuous learning will help you stay ahead of the game.

5. Develop leadership skills: A manager needs to be a good leader. Work on developing your leadership skills by taking on responsibilities, managing teams, and learning from your mistakes. 

Don’t forget to save this post and put these tips to practice. Add your plans to your vision board so you can keep working on getting that leadership role you are after.

It was one that I really did not expect and has nothing to do with being smart!

This skill is: Being bilingual!

Being bilingual is an incredibly valuable skill in the workforce. It allows you to communicate with a larger group of people and can make you a more competitive candidate for job opportunities. Additionally, it can open up opportunities for international travel and business. Studies have shown that bilingual individuals also have better cognitive abilities and problem-solving skills.

Many companies also have multiple locations (especially in Spanish speaking countries). The first company I worked at, my current company and my husband’s company all have facilities in Mexico. Having those bilingual skills open many doors and eliminates a communication barrier making you be more trustable in gathering information, problem solving, and training. 

This is often not emphasized enough! Many students opt for languages such a French, German, etc. But Spanish is extremely relevant in the US and is definitely an advantage once we enter the workforce!

There is not an exact recipe but there are things you could do to eliminate some of the barriers.

1️⃣ This is the most important one❗️ Pick your managers wisely. This is the person that is going to assign, approve and support your projects and your growth! If you need help, they can back you up, especially against some biased ppl. They will also clear and make a path for you to grow and be your ally. So ask tons of questions during those interviews ☝🏼

2️⃣ Find a community 👩‍👩‍👧‍👧 This can be company ERGs, affinity groups, volunteer group or online community such as Latina Engineer and our conference. This will help you find a place where you belong and give you the confidence to know you can succeed. You can also find great friends, role models and mentors there 😉

3️⃣ Be prepared at all times. Is there a meeting coming up? Do your research. Know as much as you can. Become trusted and stick to your commitments. Work on creating an impeccable work ethic and show that you are fully committed and open to learning. Slowly you can become the person to go to. You can also use your personal information (or preferred). So, when you leave your job and access to that work email, you don’t loose those connections.

If its scary, it means you are growing.

There are so many changes that make us feel uncomfortable and maybe even a bit scary.

⭐️Graduating and starting a new job. or maybe going after your masters.
⭐️Relocating to a new city with a new job.
⭐️Leading a new big project that you are still learning about.

These are all valid reasons to feel uneasy but definitely don’t stop! This is one of the things I address in one of my talks. “Feel the fear and do it anyway”

This has gotten me through so many challenges in my life and career.

Let me break it down into 3 steps to follow if you identify with this:

1️⃣Validate your feelings. You don’t have to fully understand them or justify them, but know that it is okay to feel them. Once you do, put them aside and take a deep breath 😮‍💨 

2️⃣Name the reasons what you are doing the thing that’s uncomfortable or scary. Are these important enough? Will the reward be better than the temporary feeling.

3️⃣Break the challenge or task into small steps to make it more digestible and easier to track progress. This way is easier to change without feeling overwhelmed. Don’t give up.

Next thing you know, it is in your past and on to the next challenge. Repeat this process as needed 😉

It is not always perfect and happy, and many won’t show the work and tears behind it. 

Honestly, it is not a nice thing to think about. I barely record the good as it is, so I am way less likely to record my lows. However, being open about it and sharing it makes it more achievable and realistic. 

We don’t automatically jump to success, there are many obstacles in the way. Immigrants, Latinas in engineering and women in STEM can have it even harder 💪🏼

It would be really easy for me to post all of my trip pictures or gifts that I got for my birthday, etc. But all of these didn’t come without hard work and planning.

I would not buy anything expensive, until I knew I could afford it. It has been a slow and steady growth. There were times where I would not see results and was ready to quit. Does it ever get better for the regular people?

That answer is still challenging, but my perseverance has shown me that sometimes I need to push just a bit more. Last year, about this time, I felt extremely frustrated, I would cry often because I felt stuck. Both my husband and I weren’t seeing enough progress at our job roles. It really felt like we were getting nowhere. Then in August all of that changed and I literally cried again, but this time because I felt like we had made it. 

Today things are a lot different as we continue to explore our roles, our goals and what plans we want to do. There are still many unknowns and I have also gone through huge body and mind challenges this past month. But as always, there are ups and downs and I am hopeful we will continue figuring it out.

🪩I picked a local school where I could commute and save the extra $$ to live on campus (and out of state). I wanted the degree not a fancy school name.

🪩I was able to have healthy food options because I was having meals at home and even packing lunch, as some of you might know, I barely cook.

🪩 I looked for scholarships to help off-set school. scholarships covered about 75% of my education and was literally able to only spend $300 per month on gas and other misc. expenses.

🪩Once I was done with school, I once again stayed home and found a job that I could drive to.

🪩It was an hour drive one way, but gas was way cheaper than moving on my own. This only lasted for about 8 months until it made sense to move closer.

🪩Once I landed a job, I negotiated and got my first salary up by almost 10k. This all helped me be able to save aggressively the first 6 months, pay off my student loans and buy a car, because my old one kept breaking down.

🪩Once I moved out, I didn’t move out alone, splitting rent in half so my expenses were still not excessive. And I am not trying to influence everyone of this step, but getting married and having the same goals, doubled the capacity we had to achieve them way sooner.

Thanks to that, I am now closer than ever to independent freedom and have set a firm date on my next big goal. This was something that I always talked about but never finalized a timeline. 

And the 10k I saved very early in my career, have been the foundation of everything else that my husband and I have been able to build together and multiplied. 

Needless to say, I am still a hard budgeter and opt to live below our means to continue creating wealth and security within our family, that as immigrants we didn’t always have.

 It’s very hard for me to share my long term goals with people in general because of all the opinions and negative reactions.

So you want to land your dream engineering role, then keep reading.

Whether you are a student or professional, there are specific steps that you must follow. It is not enough to just have the degree anymore! 

If you look at applications on Linkedin, you are able to see how many people have applied and you will see that THERE IS A LOT OF COMPETITION. 

But no worries, just follow these steps:
🪩Identify your priorities. What are you looking (pay, location, hybrid balance, remote, environment, team size, amenities, benefits, etc) Only if you know these you will know what that DREAM job is for you and you only. 
🪩Look for roles on multiple platforms to guide you, but ALWAYS apply directly on the company sites. (Try to skip recruiters if you can. You will have more advocating power for what you want)
🪩Make reminders to continuously check those company career sites. You never know when something is going to open. 
🪩Try to make a connection with someone in the company. They might be your key to get inside. Or attend events where you can stand out: like at our conference career fair. It gets you a free interview without the pre-filter process. Way to get in front of the company!
🪩Don’t use a 1 resume fits all. Make sure you look at their specific details and make sure you can match it as close as you can. 
🪩Research the things/skills you might not meet so you are familiar with them even if you are not a pro at it, but show you can develop those skills. 
🪩If you can, opt for in-person interviews. And ask questions relevant to their products/services. 
🪩Make sure you and your potential manager are a good fit. They will have a large impact in how your work days will be.

Good luck!

Listen there are some scenarios when it simply makes no sense to go for a masters, but every scenario is different so as always, do what makes sense for you.

If you are trying to decide, keep reading to see if you are in any of these categories so that can make the best decision. 

📚You are graduating soon and have no internships. 

A masters in not the solution to this problem. Instead, start getting involved in clubs and extra curricular activities. Find a Co-op for your last semester so you start getting experience. A masters will not give you the hands on experience you need and that companies want to see when hiring.

📚You want to do a masters right after a bachelors but have more than 20k in debt already

While a masters might be covered by your institution, it is not smart to sit on those loans. These will start to gain interest and you will be hooked into an endless payment loop. If this is your case, opt for finding a company that you can work for and that will pay for your masters, this way you can begin to pay down the loans instead of accumulating more. Listen to me, you do not want to be paying forever. 

📚You are not sure what you want to do with your career.

Getting a masters does not always means a better job or a better career. If you are not sure of what you like or want to do, a masters wont solve that issue. Look for a rotational program instead that will let you experience different roles (and even cities) during your first years as a professional. You will learn that not all careers need a masters to be successful.

📚You think you will have a higher salary right of the bat just because you will get a masters.

Unfortunately, a masters will not give you priority access to a higher salary. Unless, you have experience already. So don’t rush and get it right after a bachelors. Get experience, learn the field, then when you are ready and you can count  the true benefits of a masters, go for it!

Starting a new engineering job can be both exciting and daunting. One of the keys to success is to make a great first impression. 

While it’s important to be yourself, it’s also helpful to think about how you present yourself during your first few days of work. Here’s why:

👔First impressions matter. By keeping things neutral during your initial encounters with colleagues, you’ll have more freedom to show your true colors later on.

🚧You want to get familiar with the environment, so you don’t wear something inappropriate. It’s important to dress appropriately and safely, but you may not know what that means until you’ve been on the job for a few days.

With those points in mind, here are some things to avoid during your first few days:

💄Wearing too much makeup or an intricate hairstyle. Unfortunately, women in STEM fields are often judged more harshly on their appearance, so it’s best to avoid anything too bold during your first few days.

👗Dressing too casual or too dressed up. It’s best to play it safe and dress in neutral clothing until you get a better sense of what’s appropriate. If you are in manufacturing or other areas that visit sites, this will be very important. The first few days I opt for neutral blouses, slacks and common office shoes. 

📢Being too loud or aggressive. As the new person on the team, it’s important to have an open mind and be willing to learn instead of trying to prove yourself.

Of course, these tips are just recommendations. You know yourself best, so use your own judgement when deciding how to present yourself. If you decide to follow these tips and wait a few days, use that time to observe and learn about your new work environment, and then you can start to let your personality shine through.

Are you a college student looking for guidance to help you succeed while avoiding student debt? Check out these six helpful tips:

📓Step 1: University Choice

Don’t assume that a more expensive or prestigious university equals greater success. While elite institutions can provide access to more resources and may stand out on an application, obtaining a degree from any accredited institution can still lead to success. Focus on your goals, and choose a university that aligns with them.

📔Step 2: Community College

Consider starting at a community college, but do so with a plan in place. Ensure that all classes transfer, and don’t stay longer than necessary. Take courses that will help you earn a bachelor’s degree, and seek guidance from a counselor who understands STEM career requirements. This will save you a lot of money and they even have scholarships.

📕Step 3: Internships

Secure internships as early as possible, even before starting college. Some companies will accept high school graduates. Gaining experience early on will help you better understand your courses, lead to better job opportunities, and result in higher pay.

📗Step 4: Summer savings

Look for paid internships, and save the earnings to pay for the next semester. Don’t overlook this opportunity, as an internship can lead to a year-long co-op and will give you experience and higher pay throughout the year.

📘Step 5: Scholarship Applications

Apply to scholarships everywhere, with a focus on smaller, local ones or those that align with your background. For example, scholarships may be available specifically for Latina women.

📙Step 6: Avoid Loans

Try to avoid taking out loans as much as possible, as they can take a long time to pay off. It is okay to take some when really necessary as long as they are in moderation. My recommendation would be no more than 15k in total for a bachelors.

📍By following these tips, you can set yourself up for college success and financial stability. Don’t forget to follow for more helpful tips!

So math isn’t your BFF but you’re into engineering, then consider going the engineering tech route. These programs are more hands-on and less focused on complex math theories. They work on problem-solving skills, use tech tools, and require less math classes. 

These programs are all about real-world applications. You’ll be turning theory into action, which is way more exciting than getting lost in complicated equations.

These are just some of the jobs you could land with an engineering tech degree:

⚙️Engineering Technician: 

You could be the person who turns the blueprints into reality. Whether it’s testing products, troubleshooting issues, or working on prototypes, your practical skills will be in demand.

🖥️CAD Designer/Drafter:

 Ever wanted to bring designs to life on a computer? With Computer-Aided Design (CAD) skills, you can create detailed technical drawings for everything from buildings to machinery.

📐Quality Control Technician: 

Your attention to detail can shine in quality control. Ensuring products meet standards and troubleshooting any glitches that pop up – you’ll be the guardian of quality.

🦾Automation Technician: 

As companies embrace more automated processes, you could be the expert ensuring that the machines run smoothly. Troubleshooting and maintaining automated systems? That’s your domain.

🛠️Field Service Technician: 

Get ready to hit the road! You might be installing, maintaining, and repairing equipment directly on-site. It’s like being the superhero who fixes things right where they’re needed.

🧰Manufacturing Support Specialist: 

Ever wondered how things are made on a large scale? As a manufacturing support specialist, you’d be the go-to person for making sure production lines run smoothly and efficiently.

I started my career in the manufacturing engineering field, and after working in manufacturing for about 4 years, I transitioned into a design role in corporate. There has been a lot of changes such as learning about R&D, patents, safety, and more. It also came with lifestyle changes such as going from in person to a hybrid work environment and traveling internationally. 

Overall, it is just a very different environment. I feel like this newer step in my career fits a lot better with my lifestyle and the things I do outside of work. It has also helped me not feel so tired and be able to dedicate more time to my outside of work life and activities.

It is still strange not being in the same building as manufacturing and only visiting when I travel.  Here are a few reasons why I don’t miss it:

1. Stress Levels: The manufacturing industry is known for its fast-paced and high-pressure environment. While it kept me on a high for problem solving it also added significant stress to my daily work life. 
2.  Work-Life Balance: The demanding nature of the job requires mfg jobs to be on-site every day.  I would find myself running around for hours which took a toll on my overall well-being and health. Did I mention I also gained weight during the last 2 years because of the habits I developed?
3. Too Many Tasks: In my previous role, I often found myself putting out fires that would distract me from other more engineering and creative tasks. In mfg I was wearing too many hats.
4. Limited Environment: Manufacturing jobs are often dominated by men, leading to less diversity. However, manufacturing vs corporate is also very different, and as a fashion girly, I was often limited. Now I am surrounded by a larger team, more diversity, and prettier outfits 😉

This is not to say that manufacturing sucks, but depending on what you like, it will be a different fit. If you like to be hands on, then manufacturing might be the perfect fit!

Thinking about diving into the engineering world? 🚀  Engineering offers unlimited opportunities, however it might not be everyone’s ideal path.

Here are 5 signs that it might not be for you:

🧮You don’t like math:

Calculations and formulas are an everyday occurrence in this field, so it’s crucial to become comfortable with numbers. Don’t be afraid of them, with enough practice (and new tools becoming available every day) you can master the numbers!

🧗🏻‍♀️Fear of Challenges:

Engineering is known for being heavy on problem solving. If you’re hesitant to confront problems head-on and accept challenges that no one else has faced before, the experience can quickly become overwhelming.

👥You prefer to work alone:

It is a misconception that engineers tend to work alone. Companies often have multiple engineers who work together on projects. Some roles also include project management and even customer interaction. While maybe some of us are introverts, If aren’t a fan of collaboration, some engineering might not be for you.

⏰You are impatient:

Engineering projects can take time (even years), and problem-solving might not happen overnight. This is especially true when you are working on complex projects that might go through many failures before succeeding. As an engineer progress can be slow, but that long sought success can be amazing.

🧬You are not a STEM enthusiast:

If you don’t find STEM fascinating, engineering might not be the best fit. Engineers must stay at the top of innovation and cutting-edge technology. If that doesn’t excite you, engineering will not be a good long-term fit.

❗️Remember, these are just hints, not roadblocks. I am a strong believer that there is a good career within engineering and STEM because of the large amount of opportunities available.

For those who have a passion for problem-solving, innovation, and making a difference in the world, engineering can be an incredibly rewarding career choice. If you’re considering a career in engineering, take some time to explore the different paths available and see if it might be the right fit for you.
